      "role": "user",
      "content": "That custom allocator idea is a good start, but I'm worried about the overhead of maintaining a linked list of all allocations in real-time on this hardware.\n\nIs there a way to use memory watermarking or stack/heap \"canaries\" to detect where the corruption or exhaustion is actually happening? Specifically, if I'm seeing a slow creep in heap usage, how can I effectively monitor the fragmentation or find out which specific modules are responsible for the most \"unclaimed\" memory blocks before the system hits the watchdog limit?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In that case, memory watermarking and stack/heap \"canaries\" can be a more suitable approach to detect memory leaks and fragmentation without the overhead of maintaining a linked list of all allocations.\n\n**Memory Watermarking:**\n\nMemory watermarking involves periodically checking the heap's free memory against a threshold value, known as the \"watermark.\" When the free memory falls below the watermark, it indicates that the heap is becoming fragmented or exhausted. You can implement a simple watermarking scheme using a moving average of the free memory size over time.\n\nHere's a high-level outline of the steps:\n\n1.  Initialize the watermark value to a reasonable estimate of the maximum heap size.\n2.  Periodically (e.g., every 10-30 minutes) calculate the average free memory size over the last `N` allocations.\n3.  If the average free memory size falls below the watermark value, trigger an alert or take corrective action.\n\n**Stack/Heap \"Canaries\":**\n\nStack/heap \"canaries\" are small, fixed-size blocks of memory that are allocated and deallocated along with the main heap. When a canary is deallocated, it leaves behind a \"signature\" that can be used to detect memory corruption or exhaustion",
